      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1778102143313,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "stale chunk comparison:\n    same hash diff chunk?\n    chunk compare to the scope of same source, md5/sha256: very low\n        probability of collision\n        sha256 instead of md5 as its larger space\n        old and deleted chunk has obsolelte flag\ns3 write success but transaction fails:\n    wedont actually use s3. we use a inhouse data storage (bridge service)\n    which does async write with transaction support\n        bridge write fails -> failure propagate\n        bridge crash between write and ack. : WAL\n        bridge transaction coordination within itself\n    cheap clone\n        Snap_FS stores backup data as a B+ tree of chunk references order by index not hash\n         A \"clone\" of a snapshot is just copying the root pointer of that tree — O(1), \n            regardless of dataset size.\n         when a file is edited at offset 128KB, only that leaf and its \n         ancestors change. Neighboring offsets stay in the same subtree. \n        If keyed by hash, a single edit scatters modifications across the entire tree.\n    magneto delegates write to bridge, bridge writes in snap_fs and\n        also updates chunk server",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "stale chunk comparison:\n    same hash diff chunk?\n    chunk compare to the scope of same source, md5/sha256: very low\n        probability of collision\n        sha256 instead of md5 as its larger space\n        old and deleted chunk has obsolelte flag\ns3 write success but transaction fails:\n    wedont actually use s3. we use a inhouse data storage (bridge service)\n    which does async write with transaction support\n        bridge write fails -> failure propagate\n        bridge crash between write and ack. : WAL\n        bridge transaction coordination within itself\n    cheap clone\n        Snap_FS stores backup data as a B+ tree of chunk references order by index not hash\n         A \"clone\" of a snapshot is just copying the root pointer of that tree — O(1), \n            regardless of dataset size.\n         when a file is edited at offset 128KB, only that leaf and its \n         ancestors change. Neighboring offsets stay in the same subtree. \n        If keyed by hash, a single edit scatters modifications across the entire tree.\n    magneto delegates write to bridge, bridge writes in snap_fs and\n        also updates chunk server",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
